{{For|the novel|Tender Shoots}}
'''Green shoots''' is a term used colloquially and propagandistically to indicate signs of economic recovery during an [[economic downturn]]. It was first used in this sense by [[Norman Lamont (1942)|Norman Lamont]], the then [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] of the [[United Kingdom]], during the [[Early 1990s recession|1991 Recession]].<ref>{{cite news | last=Sparrow | first=Andrew | title=No 10 disowns minister's 'green shoots' comment | date=2009-03-18 | publisher=Guardian UK | accessdate=2009-06-26 | url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/mar/18/vera-baird-green-shoots}}</ref> At the time, Chancellor Lamont was criticized for "insensitivity".<ref name="BBC Green Shoots">''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7828549.stm 'Green shoots' remarks defended ]'', BBC News, 14 January 2009</ref> The phrase was used again by [[Baroness Vadera]], former [[Department for Business, Enterprise and Regulatory Reform|Business Minister]] of the UK in January, 2009 to refer to signs of economic recovery during the [[late-2000s recession]], again to criticism from the media and opposition politicians.<ref name="BBC Green Shoots"/> The U.S. media started to use the phrase to describe domestic economic conditions in February 2009 when in New York Times quoted [[Bruce Kasman]], chief economist at JPMorgan Chase as saying, "It's too early to get excited, but I think there are a couple of green shoots that say  we're not going down as heavily in the first quarter [of 2009] as we were in the fourth quarter [of 2008]."<ref>{{cite news | last=Healy | first=Jack | title=Data Hints As Slowing of Decline | date=2009-02-17 | publisher=NYTimes | accessdate=2009-06-21 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/17/business/economy/17econ.html}}</ref> The [[Federal Reserve]] Chairman, [[Ben Bernanke]], made the first public use of the phrase by a Fed official in a March 15, 2009 interview with [[CBS]] [[60 Minutes]].  Since February and March 2009, it has been used increasingly in the media<ref>{{cite news | last=Frierson | first=Burton | title=Green shoots in U.S. jobs, factories and indicators | date=2009-06-18 | publisher=reuters | accessdate=2009-06-23 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/ousiv/idUSTRE55B37720090618?sp=true}}</ref> and by a number of commentators{{Who|date=June 2009}} to refer to positive economic data and statistics during the late-2000s (decade) recession.{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}}

