{{redirect-distinguish|Ophelemic|Thelema{{!}}Thelemic}}
'''Ophelimity''' is an economic concept introduced by [[Vilfredo Pareto]] as a measure of purely economic satisfaction, so he could use the already well-established term [[utility]] as a measure of a more broadly based satisfaction encompassing other dimensions as well, such as the ethical, moral, religious, and political.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Paretian Welfare Theory: Some Neglected Aspects |journal=The Journal of Political Economy |date=1969-01-02 |first=Vincent J. |last=Tarascio |volume=77 |issue=1 |pages=1–20| id= |jstor=1829062 |doi=10.1086/259490}}</ref> As such, it corresponds to the sense in which utility is often used in economic calculations. [[Irving Fisher]] proposed replacing ophelimity (and thus utility as it is commonly construed) with the term ''wantability''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://economistsview.typepad.com/economistsview/2008/03/ophelimity-vs-w.html |title=Ophelimity vs. Wantability |accessdate=2011-05-20 |last=Thoma |first=Mark |date=2008-03-23}}</ref>

==See also==
*[[Autotelic]], another term for whether a thing has useful contingency (purpose through specific utility) or is an ends with purpose unto itself.

